# Raw Dataset — Endometrial Organoid Single-Cell RNA-seq

This project uses a publicly available **single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq)** dataset of healthy human **endometrial epithelial organoids (EEOs)** generated by **García-Alonso et al. (2021)**.

The dataset provides a transcriptomic atlas of endometrial organoid cultures and enables the study of epithelial subpopulations, stem/progenitor markers, and hormone-driven cellular dynamics at single-cell resolution.

---

## Biological background

The human endometrium undergoes cyclic regeneration, suggesting the presence of resident adult stem cells.

**Endometrial organoids** are 3D in vitro cultures derived from patient tissue that closely recapitulate:

- epithelial structure  
- hormonal responsiveness  
- regeneration processes  
- differentiation programs  

Combined with **single-cell RNA-seq**, organoids allow:

- cellular heterogeneity profiling  
- differential gene expression analysis  
- stem cell marker discovery  
- translational and precision medicine research  

---

## Dataset composition

Includes:

- Healthy human endometrial epithelial organoid cells  
- Hormone-treated and control conditions  
- Single-cell gene expression matrix  
- Cell-level metadata and annotations  

Main populations:

- epithelial (luminal, glandular, ciliated)  
- immune  
- stromal-like  
- endothelial/support  

Note: This project focuses primarily on epithelial subpopulations.

## Dataset scale

- ~118,672 single cells
- ~27,254 genes (features)
- High-dimensional sparse expression matrix (UMI counts)
- AnnData structure compatible with Scanpy / Seurat conversion


---

## File format

Original format: .h5ad (AnnData / Scanpy format)
In this project, the file is converted to: .h5seurat (Seurat compatible)


### Conversion workflow

The dataset is converted using:

.h5ad → SeuratDisk::Convert() → .h5seurat → Seurat object

This enables cross-platform interoperability between Python (Scanpy) and R (Seurat).


## Download

Due to size and licensing, raw data are **not included** in this repository.

Download directly from the official source:

https://cellgeni.cog.sanger.ac.uk/vento/reproductivecellatlas/endometrium_organoid.h5ad

